			<p>Halal catering matters. For Muslim guests, it isn't a preference — it's a requirement rooted in faith. And for hosts planning multi-cultural events, getting halal right is the difference between making everyone feel welcome and unintentionally excluding part of the room. After fifteen years of catering across Vancouver, we've seen how often halal is treated as an afterthought. It shouldn't be. Here's what to ask, what to look for, and why it matters.</p>

			<h2>What "Halal" Actually <em>Means</em></h2>
			<p>Halal refers to food permissible under Islamic dietary law. For meat, that means animals are raised, slaughtered, and processed according to specific standards — humanely, with a prayer recitation, and with separation from non-halal products throughout the supply chain.</p>
			<p>The key phrase is <em>halal-certified</em>. Certification means a third-party authority has verified the supplier's entire process, not just the slaughter. In British Columbia, certification typically comes from organisations like the Halal Monitoring Authority or BC Halal Food Council.</p>

			<h2>Why It Matters at <em>Multi-Cultural Events</em></h2>
			<p>Vancouver's most beautiful events — <a href="/weddings">South Asian weddings</a>, corporate galas, community celebrations — bring together guests from many faiths and traditions. At a wedding of 300 guests, you'll likely have Muslim, Hindu, Sikh, Jain, vegetarian, vegan, and gluten-free attendees in the same room.</p>
			<p>If your menu isn't halal-certified, your Muslim guests have to skip the meat dishes entirely. That's a small but meaningful exclusion in what should be a celebration of unity.</p>

			<h2>The Right Questions to <em>Ask Your Caterer</em></h2>
			<ul>
				<li>Is your meat halal-certified? Which certification body?</li>
				<li>Are halal and non-halal proteins prepared in separate kitchen areas?</li>
				<li>Are utensils, cutting boards, and pans dedicated to halal preparation?</li>
				<li>Can you provide certification documentation if requested?</li>
				<li>What's your protocol for cross-contamination?</li>
			</ul>
			<p>A good caterer answers these without hesitation. If the answer is vague, that's information.</p>

			<h2>Halal Doesn't Mean <em>Less Variety</em></h2>
			<p>Some hosts assume going halal limits their menu options. The opposite is true. Indian cuisine is built around halal-friendly proteins — chicken, lamb, goat — and rich vegetarian dishes that need no certification at all. Butter chicken, lamb rogan josh, dum biryani, paneer butter masala, dal makhani: all part of a halal-friendly menu by default when sourced correctly.</p>

			<h2>What We Do at <em>Sula</em></h2>
			<p>All chicken and lamb across our <a href="/corporate">corporate catering</a> menus is halal-certified, sourced from trusted local BC suppliers. Our kitchens maintain dedicated areas for halal preparation, and we provide certification documentation on request.</p>
			<p>For corporate events, we treat halal as standard — not as a special request.</p>

			<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
			<p>The right caterer makes halal feel effortless. No special-request menus. No awkward questions at the buffet line. Just food that everyone can eat, prepared with care. <a href="https://sulaindianrestaurant.com/request-a-quote/">Request a quote</a> and we'll walk you through our halal sourcing in detail.</p>

